America during the Cold War and the Limits of Non-Alignment -- tA Non-Aligned Continent: Africa in the Global Imaginary of Socialist Yugoslavia -- tMobilities and Migrations -- tTransnational Educational Strategies during the Cold War: Students from the Global South in Socialist Yugoslavia, 1961–91 -- tNew Borders, Old Solidarities: (Post-)Cold War Genealogies of Mobility along the “Balkan Route” -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter a summit in Belgrade in September 1961, socialist Yugoslavia, led by President Josip Broz Tito until his death in 1980, initiated a movement with states in the Global South. The Non-Aligned Movement not only offered an alternative to the Cold War polarization between NATO and the Warsaw Pact but also expressed the hopes of a world emerging from colonial domination.Socialist Yugoslavia and the Non-Aligned Movement investigates the Non-Aligned Movement both as a top-down, interstate initiative and as a site for transnational exchange in science, art and culture, architecture, education, and industry. Re-invigorating older debates by consulting newly available sources, the volume challenges studies that marginalize the role of socialist Yugoslavia in the Non-Aligned Movement. Contributors address topics such as women’s involvement, antifascism and anti-imperialism, cultural and educational exchange, tensions in Yugoslav diplomacy, competing understandings of economic development, the role of the Yugoslav construction company Energoprojekt, Yugoslav relations with Latin America and Africa, and contemporary support for refugees and asylum seekers as a kind of practical and affective afterlife of Yugoslavia’s non-aligned commitments. Socialist Yugoslavia and the Non-Aligned Movement offers an innovative approach to one of the twentieth century’s most important international movements and confronts issues of economic, social, and cultural rights that remain relevant today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCold War. 0aNonalignmentzYugoslavia. 0aSocialismzYugoslavia. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh1 aBalmazović, Ðorđe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonfiglioli, Chiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCosovschi, Agustin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDugonjic-Rodwin, Leonora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenig, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJakovina, Tvrtko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirn, Gal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoleśnik, Ljiljana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMladenović, Ivica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPiśkur, Bojana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRadonjić, Nemanja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRamśak, Jure, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRazsa, Maple, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSekulić, Dubravka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStubbs, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStubbs, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTurajlić, Mila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVidekanić, Bojana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilletts, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228015802?locatt=mode:leg